Task 1

Data set annualpopu was selected

The data set shows yearly average population rates for the old federal states in Germany (given in 1000 inhabitants)

First, have a brief look at this data set.

As you can see from the faces on the above, the amount of data for both variables increased with the year. An increase in face width, for example, shows an increase in the total number of inhabitants, which also reflects general demographic trends in Germany’s old federal states.

At last a Two-dimensional kernel density estimation

library(MASS)
library("RColorBrewer")
colors <- brewer.pal(5, "Reds")
z <- kde2d(annualpopu$Inhabitants,annualpopu$Unemployed,n=500, lims = c(50000,70000,0,3500))
plot(annualpopu$Inhabitants,annualpopu$Unemployed, xlab="Inhabitant", ylab="Unemployed", pch=21, bg = "yellow")
contour(z, drawlabels=FALSE, nlevels=10, col=colors, add=TRUE)

The figure above shows the density of the data and from which we can also conclude that in the early stage, the total number of inhabitants grew rapidly, and in the mid-term, the number of unemployed experienced rapid growth.

Task 2

Theoretical example

the random vector \(\left(X_{i}, Y_{i}\right)^{T}\)follows the uniform distribution with density\[f(x, y)=c \cdot 1_{[(x, y) \in M]} \text { ， } M=\left\{(x, y) \in \mathbb{R}^{2} ; 0<x<y<1\right\}\]and M is a 2 dimensional Lebesgue measurable set, from which we can get \(c=2\) and also get

1.the density function\[f(x, y)=2 \cdot 1_{[(x, y) \in M]} \] 2.marginal density \[ f_{X}(x)=\int_{x}^{1} f(x, y) d y=2(1-x),x \in(0,1) \] 3.marginal density \[f_{Y}(y)=\int_{0}^{y} f(x, y) d x=2 y ,y \in(0,1) \] 4.not independent,for\[f_{X}(x)f_{Y}(y)=4(1-x)y\neq2,(x, y) \in M\] \[E X_{i}=\int_{0}^{1} 2 x(1-x) d x=\frac{1}{3} \] \[E Y_{i}=\int_{0}^{1} 2 y^{2} d y=\frac{2}{3}\]

\[\operatorname{Var}\left(X_{i}\right)= \mathrm{E}\left(X_{i}^{2}\right)-\left(\mathrm{E} X_{i}\right)^{2}=\int_{0}^{1} 2 x^{2}(1-x) d x-\frac{1}{3^2}=\frac{1}{18} \]

\[ \operatorname{Var}\left( Y_{i}\right)= \mathrm{E}\left(Y_{i}^{2}\right)-\left(\mathrm{E} Y_{i}\right)^{2}=\int_{0}^{1} 2 y^{3} d y-\frac{2^2}{3^2}=\frac{1}{18} \] \[ \operatorname{cov}\left(X_{i}, Y_{i}\right)=\mathrm{E}\left(X_{i} \ Y_{i}\right)-\mathrm{E} X_{i} \mathrm{E} Y_{i}=\int_{0} ^{1}\int_{0}^{y} xy f(x, y) d x d y-\frac{2}{3^2} =\frac{1}{36} \] \[ \operatorname{Var}\left(X_{i}, Y_{i}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cc} \frac{1}{18} & \frac{1}{36} \\ \frac{1}{36} & \frac{1}{18} \end{array}\right) \]

Practical example

At first, calculate the CDF of x. \[ F_{X}=\int_{-\infty}^{x} 2(1-u) 1_{u \in(0,1)} d u= \begin{cases}0 & \text { if } x<0 \\ 2 x-x^{2} & \text { if } x \in(0,1) \\ 1 & \text { if } x>1\end{cases} \] and the corresponding quantile function is

\[ F_{X}^{-1}(z^*)=1-\sqrt{1-z^*} \quad z^* \in(0,1) \] \[ F_{Y}=\int_{-\infty}^{y} 2u 1_{u \in(0,1)} d u= \begin{cases}0 & \text { if } y<0 \\ y^{2} & \text { if } y \in(0,1) \\ 1 & \text { if } y>1\end{cases} \] then calculate both conditional CDF of x and the corresponding quantile function \[ f_{y\mid x}= \frac{f_{x, y}(x,y)}{f_{ x}(x)}=\frac{1}{1-x}\quad x \in(0,1) \] \[ F_{Y \mid X}=\int_{-\infty}^{y}\frac{1}{1-x}dy= \begin{cases}0 & \text { if } y<x \\ \frac{y-x}{1-x} & \text { if } y \in(x,1) \\ 1 & \text { if } y>1\end{cases} \]

\[ F_{Y \mid X}^{-1}(z)=z(1-x)+x, \quad z \in(0,1) \]

n <- 10000
set.seed(1)

Z_1 <- runif(n)
par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(ecdf(Z_1), main = "Empirical d.f. of Z_1")
hist(Z_1, col = "gray", breaks = ceiling(10))

X <- 1-sqrt(1-Z_1)
xSeq <- seq(0,1, length = 10000)
par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(ecdf(X), main = "Empirical d.f. of X")
lines((2*xSeq-xSeq^2) ~ xSeq, col = "red", lty = 2, lwd = 2)
legend("topleft", legend = c("Empirical d.f.", "Theoretical d.f."), col = c("black", "red"), lty = c(1,2), lwd =c (2,2))
hist(X, freq = F, col = "gray", breaks = ceiling(sqrt(n)))
lines((2-2*xSeq) ~ xSeq, col = "red", lty = 2, lwd = 2)
legend("topright", legend = c("Empirical density", "Theoretical density"), col = c("black", "red"), lty = c(2,2), lwd = c(2,2))

As for the conditional distribution of X given Y

n <- 10000
set.seed(2)

Z <- runif(n)
par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(ecdf(Z), main = "Empirical d.f. of Z")
hist(Z, col = "gray", breaks = ceiling(10))

X_Y <- Z*(1-Z_1)+Z_1
ySeq <- seq(0,1, length = 10000)
par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(ecdf(X_Y), main = "Empirical d.f. of X")
lines((ySeq-xSeq)/(1-xSeq) ~ ySeq, col = "red", lty = 2, lwd = 2)
legend("topleft", legend = c("Empirical d.f.", "Theoretical d.f."), col = c("black", "red"), lty = c(1,2), lwd =c (2,2))
hist(X_Y, freq = F, col = "gray", breaks = ceiling(sqrt(n)))
lines(1/(1-xSeq) ~ ySeq, col = "red", lty = 2, lwd = 2)
legend("topright", legend = c("Empirical density", "Theoretical density"), col = c("black", "red"), lty = c(2,2), lwd = c(2,2))
